<module>
  <title>ethnonyms</title>
  <p>Ethnonyms are <a href="?xx=nouns/common_nouns">common nouns</a> which describe a person in terms of their ethno-cultural heritage.</p>
  <p>e.g. <m>Gàidheal</m> <en>Gael</en>, <m>Cruithneach</m> <en>Pict</en>, <m>Ceilteach</m> <en>Celt</en>.</p>
  <p>cf. <a href="?xx=nouns/demonyms">demonyms</a></p>
  <p>Members of extended families, derived from surnames &amp;c –</p>
  <ul>
    <li><m>Frisealach</m> <en>a Fraser</en> (Calder 1923: 105), cf. Friseal</li>
    <li><m>Caimbeulach</m> <en>a Campbell</en> (Calder 1923: 105), cf. Caimbeul</li>
    <li><m>Duibhneach</m> <en>a Campbell</en>  (Calder 1923: 105) cf. ??</li>
    <li><m>Camshronach</m> <en>a Cameron</en> (Calder 1923: 105) cf. Camshron</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Often used in <a href="?xx=nouns/anthroponymic_name_descriptions">anthroponymic name-descriptions</a> and in ‘<a href="?xx=nouns/grouponyms">grouponyms</a>’.</p>
</module>
